english:
  title: A Memorial Presented to the Prime Ministers on Behalf of King Sŏm
  author: Min Chi
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In this present age, the realm's territory spans wide and its people number vast—since the universe itself was formed, none have compared to the multitude of today. Yet I have never heard tell of a single soul left without their proper place, nor a single thing denied its rightful use. This truly owes to the manifold ministers' efforts in assisting the throne and harmonizing governance.

    I humbly reflect that the former king, being the brother-in-law of King Sejong, served five successive courts for more than thirty years. Yet he took upon himself the duty of cultivating good karma and beseeching Heaven's blessings upon the sovereign. Once, failing to perceive his own stubborn delusion, he incurred Heaven's displeasure and was banished to distant western lands. Four years have passed to this day—how can the heart not ache?

    Our small realm's people are no mere wood or stone; who among them lacks the faithful devotion of a hound toward its master? Yet heaven and earth lie far divided, and the faint cry of insects carries no path to the throne. We can only weep day and night. How much more so for those of us—having once received appointment, having been blessed with favor, having attained honor and position, now grown ancient with age—how can our longing be less than a hundredfold?

    Yet thunder's majesty shakes all creation. Gripped by awe and terror, I know not what to do. Only gazing upward at heaven's light have I lingered at the sea's edge, unable to advance. Now, esteemed prime ministers, you shall ensure that within all the realm not a single thing lacks its proper place. If we fail to fulfill this lingering affection ere we fade like morning dew with the setting sun, we shall be said to have betrayed this glorious age, our regret reaching even to the Yellow Springs.

    Therefore, bearing my infirmity, I have taken to the road, enduring countless hardships. By fortune's grace, I yet draw breath. Crawling forth, I humbly beseech you: take pity on our sovereign, exiled far from home, who has endured these long years. Take pity on this aged frame that has journeyed over three thousand li. May you speak eloquently on our behalf, unfold the sacred grace, and turn our sovereign's steps homeward across ten thousand li. Then we, though ancient, shall prove no less devoted than turtle or serpent in offering our very lives in gratitude.
  footnotes:
    - King Sejong (세조) is likely a reference to a specific historical figure; the text's chronological details suggest this memorial addresses the exile and potential restoration of a royal person.
    - The 'Yellow Springs' (황천) is a classical reference to the underworld or the realm of the deceased, emphasizing the urgency and depth of the petitioner's longing.
    - The turtle and serpent (거북과 뱀) are classical symbols of loyalty and devotion in East Asian literature, representing unwavering commitment.
